Gene, sure evolutionary algorithms have been applied to both open-ended a=
nd creative endeavors for many years before novelty search.  In fact both o=
ur introductory papers on novelty search (ALIFE-08 and ECJ 11) include sect=
ions that explicitly cite prior work in open-ended evolution as an inspirat=
ion for novelty search.  There is no doubt that they share many principles.=


Creative systems such as interactive evolution also share many principles=
 with novelty search, which is the inspiration for the publication at the r=
oot of this discussion thread.  So certainly we don&#39;t want to imply that no=
velty search is the first to explore open-endedness or creativity in evolut=
ion (much of my own work is even in creative evolutionary systems outside n=
ovelty search).  In fact, we view novelty search as a complement to the wor=
k in this area.  Diversity-preservation-mechanisms (such as speciation) and=
 coevolution also relate to novelty search in various ways.

However, novel=
ty search is the only generic (i.e. domain-general) evolutionary algorithm =
we know of that explicitly rewards phenotypic novelty and only novelty with=
 no other criteria and no awareness of the objective whatsoever (many such =
prior algorithms combine objective criteria with a drive towards diversity)=
.  To our knowledge it is also the first time that such an open-ended appro=
ach was used to show that many problems considered objective can be transfo=
rmed into non-objective problems that are actually solved better without an=
 objective (which remains a controversial yet useful discussion point).  

=
If you would like to share another algorithm that is similar then that&#39;s gr=
eat (the book you cited is a survey of many systems, and I don&#39;t know of a =
specific example in that book that works like novelty search).  Of course, =
after four years of publication reviews I would be surprised to see somethi=
ng with the same exact mechanism that our reviewers did not catch, but it&#39;s=
 a big world and you never know.  However, I would not be surprised to see =
many related ideas - of course open-ended evolution and creative evolutiona=
ry systems share much of the same inspiration as novelty search.  Our hope =
was in effect to distill the core essence of such systems into the simplest=
 possible heuristic to make its study and applicability as easy and univers=
al as possible.

It&#39;s probably also useful to note that the motivation for =
starting this discussion for me was not to argue that novelty search is &quot;su=
perior.&quot;  Rather I think its generality and simplicity make it a useful dev=
ice for investigating the impact of our field&#39;s longstanding loyalty to obj=
ective-driven algorithms and evaluation standards, in particular in domains=
 that are considered &quot;objective.&quot;  If other approaches also contribute to t=
hat discussion then all the better!

